set default parameters The use of this routine is optional. 

Colamd\+: rows with more than (knobs \mbox{[}COLAMD\+\_\+\+DENSE\+\_\+\+ROW\mbox{]} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} n\+\_\+col) entries are removed prior to ordering. Columns with more than (knobs \mbox{[}COLAMD\+\_\+\+DENSE\+\_\+\+COL\mbox{]} \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} n\+\_\+row) entries are removed prior to ordering, and placed last in the output column ordering.

COLAMD\+\_\+\+DENSE\+\_\+\+ROW and COLAMD\+\_\+\+DENSE\+\_\+\+COL are defined as 0 and 1, respectively, in colamd.\+h. Default values of these two knobs are both 0.\+5. Currently, only knobs \mbox{[}0\mbox{]} and knobs \mbox{[}1\mbox{]} are used, but future versions may use more knobs. If so, they will be properly set to their defaults by the future version of colamd\+\_\+set\+\_\+defaults, so that the code that calls colamd will not need to change, assuming that you either use colamd\+\_\+set\+\_\+defaults, or pass a (double \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*}) NULL pointer as the knobs array to colamd or symamd.

Computes the blocking parameters for a m x k times k x n matrix product 


\begin{DoxyParams}[1]{参数}
\mbox{\texttt{ in,out}}  & {\em k} & \doxylink{struct_input}{Input}\+: the third dimension of the product. Output\+: the blocking size along the same dimension. \\
\hline
\mbox{\texttt{ in,out}}  & {\em m} & \doxylink{struct_input}{Input}\+: the number of rows of the left hand side. Output\+: the blocking size along the same dimension. \\
\hline
\mbox{\texttt{ in,out}}  & {\em n} & \doxylink{struct_input}{Input}\+: the number of columns of the right hand side. Output\+: the blocking size along the same dimension.\\
\hline
\end{DoxyParams}
Given a m x k times k x n matrix product of scalar types {\ttfamily Lhs\+Scalar} and {\ttfamily Rhs\+Scalar}, this function computes the blocking size parameters along the respective dimensions for matrix products and related algorithms.

The blocking size parameters may be evaluated\+:
\begin{DoxyItemize}
\item either by a heuristic based on cache sizes;
\item or using fixed prescribed values (for testing purposes).
\end{DoxyItemize}

\doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_solve}{Solve} a triangular Sylvester equation AX + XB = C 


\begin{DoxyParams}[1]{参数}
\mbox{\texttt{ in}}  & {\em \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_addc86e8508f14411ec98f521c520f875}{A}} & the matrix \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_addc86e8508f14411ec98f521c520f875}{A}; should be square and upper triangular \\
\hline
\mbox{\texttt{ in}}  & {\em \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_a37a83060ac796961b44991c836f083f7}{B}} & the matrix \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_a37a83060ac796961b44991c836f083f7}{B}; should be square and upper triangular \\
\hline
\mbox{\texttt{ in}}  & {\em C} & the matrix C; should have correct size.\\
\hline
\end{DoxyParams}
\begin{DoxyReturn}{返回}
the solution X.
\end{DoxyReturn}
If \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_addc86e8508f14411ec98f521c520f875}{A} is m-\/by-\/m and \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_a37a83060ac796961b44991c836f083f7}{B} is n-\/by-\/n, then both C and X are m-\/by-\/n. The (i,j)-\/th component of the Sylvester equation is   \[    \sum_{k=i}^m A_{ik} X_{kj} + \sum_{k=1}^j X_{ik} B_{kj} = C_{ij}. 
\] This can be re-\/arranged to yield\+:    \[    X_{ij} = \frac{1}{A_{ii} + B_{jj}} \Bigl( C_{ij}
    - \sum_{k=i+1}^m A_{ik} X_{kj} - \sum_{k=1}^{j-1} X_{ik} B_{kj} \Bigr).
\] It is assumed that \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_addc86e8508f14411ec98f521c520f875}{A} and \doxylink{bench__gemm_8cpp_a37a83060ac796961b44991c836f083f7}{B} are such that the numerator is never zero (otherwise the Sylvester equation does not have a unique solution). In that case, these equations can be evaluated in the order $ i=m,\ldots,1 $ and $ j=1,\ldots,n $. \Hypertarget{namespace_eigen_1_1internal_a1cb8d312c017f94570a52317fd1ece5f}\index{Eigen::internal@{Eigen::internal}!matrix\_log\_compute\_2x2@{matrix\_log\_compute\_2x2}}

{\footnotesize\ttfamily \label{namespace_eigen_1_1internal_a58a0ccf0e71d88beeb5dcf72ed0bdd5f} 
template$<$typename CMatrix, typename CINVMatrix$>$ \\

template$<$typename Decomposition$>$ \\

Reciprocal condition number estimator. 

Computing a decomposition of a dense matrix takes O(n\texorpdfstring{$^\wedge$}{\string^}3) operations, while this method estimates the condition number quickly and reliably in O(n\texorpdfstring{$^\wedge$}{\string^}2) operations.

\begin{DoxyReturn}{返回}
an estimate of the reciprocal condition number (1 / (\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}matrix\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\+\_\+1 \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} \texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}inv(matrix)\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\+\_\+1)) of matrix, given \texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}matrix\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\+\_\+1 and its decomposition. Supports the following decompositions\+: \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_full_piv_l_u}{Full\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_partial_piv_l_u}{Partial\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_d_l_t}{LDLT}, and \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_l_t}{LLT}.
\end{DoxyReturn}
\begin{DoxySeeAlso}{参见}
\doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_full_piv_l_u}{Full\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_partial_piv_l_u}{Partial\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_d_l_t}{LDLT}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_l_t}{LLT}.

an estimate of \texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}inv(matrix)\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\+\_\+1 given a decomposition of {\itshape matrix} that implements .\doxylink{sudoku_8cpp_a970d2c74caf59ac29774bbbca9baa75c}{solve()} and .\doxylink{adjoint_8cpp_a7333648f53414b05be9e4fd2f009fc22}{adjoint()}.\doxylink{sudoku_8cpp_a970d2c74caf59ac29774bbbca9baa75c}{solve()} methods.
\end{DoxyReturn}
This function implements Algorithms 4.\+1 and 5.\+1 from \href{http://www.maths.manchester.ac.uk/~higham/narep/narep135.pdf}{\texttt{ http\+://www.\+maths.\+manchester.\+ac.\+uk/\texorpdfstring{$\sim$}{\string~}higham/narep/narep135.\+pdf}} which also forms the basis for the condition number estimators in LAPACK. Since at most 10 calls to the solve method of dec are performed, the total cost is O(dims\texorpdfstring{$^\wedge$}{\string^}2), as opposed to O(dims\texorpdfstring{$^\wedge$}{\string^}3) needed to compute the inverse matrix explicitly.

The most common usage is in estimating the condition number \texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}matrix\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\+\_\+1 \texorpdfstring{$\ast$}{*} \texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}inv(matrix)\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\+\_\+1. The first term \texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}matrix\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\texorpdfstring{$\vert$}{|}\+\_\+1 can be computed directly in O(n\texorpdfstring{$^\wedge$}{\string^}2) operations.

Supports the following decompositions\+: \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_full_piv_l_u}{Full\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_partial_piv_l_u}{Partial\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_d_l_t}{LDLT}, and \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_l_t}{LLT}.

\begin{DoxySeeAlso}{参见}
\doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_full_piv_l_u}{Full\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_partial_piv_l_u}{Partial\+Piv\+LU}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_d_l_t}{LDLT}, \doxylink{class_eigen_1_1_l_l_t}{LLT}. 
\end{DoxySeeAlso}

Performs a full tridiagonalization in place 


\begin{DoxyParams}[1]{参数}
\mbox{\texttt{ in,out}}  & {\em mat} & On input, the selfadjoint matrix whose tridiagonal decomposition is to be computed. Only the lower triangular part referenced. The rest is left unchanged. On output, the orthogonal matrix Q in the decomposition if {\ttfamily extractQ} is true. \\
\hline
\mbox{\texttt{ out}}  & {\em diag} & The diagonal of the tridiagonal matrix T in the decomposition. \\
\hline
\mbox{\texttt{ out}}  & {\em subdiag} & The subdiagonal of the tridiagonal matrix T in the decomposition. \\
\hline
\mbox{\texttt{ in}}  & {\em extractQ} & If true, the orthogonal matrix Q in the decomposition is computed and stored in {\ttfamily mat}.\\
\hline
\end{DoxyParams}
Computes the tridiagonal decomposition of the selfadjoint matrix {\ttfamily mat} in place such that $ mat = Q T Q^* $ where $ Q $ is unitary and $ T $ a real symmetric tridiagonal matrix.

The tridiagonal matrix T is passed to the output parameters {\ttfamily diag} and {\ttfamily subdiag}. If {\ttfamily extractQ} is true, then the orthogonal matrix Q is passed to {\ttfamily mat}. Otherwise the lower part of the matrix {\ttfamily mat} is destroyed.

The vectors {\ttfamily diag} and {\ttfamily subdiag} are not resized. The function assumes that they are already of the correct size. The length of the vector {\ttfamily diag} should equal the number of rows in {\ttfamily mat}, and the length of the vector {\ttfamily subdiag} should be one left.

This implementation contains an optimized path for 3-\/by-\/3 matrices which is especially useful for plane fitting.

\begin{DoxyNote}{注解}
Currently, it requires two temporary vectors to hold the intermediate Householder coefficients, and to reconstruct the matrix Q from the Householder reflectors.
\end{DoxyNote}
